🔑 DSA Pattern / Concept
Pattern: Game Theory + DFS + Memoization (bitmask DP)

Why?

Two players alternately pick numbers from 1..maxCoinBag.

Once picked, a number cannot be reused.

The first player wants to know if they can force a win.

This is a perfect information game → solved by recursive search with memoization.

🧩 Key Observations
If targetTreasure == 0, first player wins immediately.

If the sum of all coin bags < targetTreasure, no one can win → return "no".

Otherwise, simulate moves:

Represent chosen bags with a bitmask (used).

At each step, try picking a bag i.

If i >= remaining target, current player wins.

Else, if the opponent cannot win from the new state, current player wins.

🔑 Edge Cases to Cover
Target = 0 → First adventurer wins immediately (yes).

Target ≤ maxCoinBag → First adventurer can pick that bag and win (yes).

Sum of all bags < target → Impossible for anyone to win (no).

General case → Use DFS + memoization with bitmask to simulate optimal play.

✅ One‑Shot Fixed Code (Handles All Edge Cases)
cpp
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

unordered_map<int,bool> memo;

bool canWin(int maxCoinBag, int target, int usedMask) {
    if (memo.count(usedMask)) return memo[usedMask];

    for (int i = 1; i <= maxCoinBag; i++) {
        int bit = 1 << (i-1);
        if (usedMask & bit) continue; // already taken

        if (i >= target) return memo[usedMask] = true;

        // If opponent cannot win after I take i
        if (!canWin(maxCoinBag, target - i, usedMask | bit)) {
            return memo[usedMask] = true;
        }
    }
    return memo[usedMask] = false;
}

int main() {
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    int T; cin >> T;
    while (T--) {
        int maxCoinBag, targetTreasure;
        cin >> maxCoinBag >> targetTreasure;

        // Edge case 1: target = 0
        if (targetTreasure == 0) {
            cout << "yes\n";
            continue;
        }

        // Edge case 2: target <= maxCoinBag
        if (targetTreasure <= maxCoinBag) {
            cout << "yes\n";
            continue;
        }

        // Edge case 3: sum of all bags < target
        int sum = maxCoinBag * (maxCoinBag + 1) / 2;
        if (sum < targetTreasure) {
            cout << "no\n";
            continue;
        }

        // General case: DFS + memoization
        memo.clear();
        cout << (canWin(maxCoinBag, targetTreasure, 0) ? "yes\n" : "no\n");
    }
    return 0;
}
🧮 Dry Run
Input: 10 11 → sum=55 ≥ 11, but DFS shows second player can always respond → "no".

Input: 10 0 → target=0 → "yes".

Input: 10 1 → target ≤ maxCoinBag → "yes".

Input: 20 300 → sum=210 < 300 → "no".

🎯 Why This Fix Works
Covers all edge cases explicitly before DFS.

Uses memoized DFS with bitmask for general case.

Efficient: maxCoinBag ≤ 20 → at most 2^20 states, manageable with memoization.

Memoize results to avoid recomputation

✅ LC‑Style C++ Code
cpp
class Solution {
public:
    unordered_map<int,bool> memo;

    bool dfs(int maxChoosableInteger, int desiredTotal, int usedMask) {
        if (memo.count(usedMask)) return memo[usedMask];

        for (int i = 1; i <= maxChoosableInteger; i++) {
            int bit = 1 << (i-1);
            if (usedMask & bit) continue; // already taken

            if (i >= desiredTotal) return memo[usedMask] = true;

            // If opponent cannot win after I take i
            if (!dfs(maxChoosableInteger, desiredTotal - i, usedMask | bit)) {
                return memo[usedMask] = true;
            }
        }
        return memo[usedMask] = false;
    }

    bool canIWin(int maxChoosableInteger, int desiredTotal) {
        // Edge case 1: target = 0
        if (desiredTotal == 0) return true;

        // Edge case 2: target <= maxChoosableInteger
        if (desiredTotal <= maxChoosableInteger) return true;

        // Edge case 3: sum of all numbers < target
        int sum = maxChoosableInteger * (maxChoosableInteger + 1) / 2;
        if (sum < desiredTotal) return false;

        memo.clear();
        return dfs(maxChoosableInteger, desiredTotal, 0);
    }
};
🔑 Why This Works
Immediate win checks:

desiredTotal == 0 → first player wins.

desiredTotal <= maxChoosableInteger → first player can pick that number.

Impossible case: If sum of all numbers < target → no one can win.

General case: DFS + memoization with bitmask simulates optimal play.

Efficient: maxChoosableInteger ≤ 20 → at most 2^20 states, manageable.

🧮 Example
Input: maxChoosableInteger=10, desiredTotal=11 → returns false (no).

Input: maxChoosableInteger=10, desiredTotal=1 → returns true (yes).
